# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-chip
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-chip/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] A **3-in-1**, **trio** or **three-in-one** is a fast-food dish consisting of chips, boiled rice (or egg fried rice), and curry sauce served in a single foil tray or plastic container.
[src:apple-chip/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It became popular in Ireland as a dish from chip shops and Chinese restaurants in the early twenty-first century.
[src:apple-chip/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It developed a cult following in the 2010s, and media outlets debated the merits of it compared to a spice bag, which became popular around the same time.
[src:apple-chip/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] Related dishes (four-, five-in one) contain additional ingredients such as chicken balls, or chicken or beef pieces.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-chip/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-chip/agedashi-dōfu] While *agedashi dōfu* is the best-known *agedashi* dish, some other dishes may be prepared with similar techniques.
[src:apple-chip/agedashi-dōfu] These include *agedashinasu* (揚げ出し茄子), using eggplant.
[src:apple-chip/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-chip/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-chip/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-chip/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apple-chip/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apple-chip/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Apple chips may be used in sandwiches and as an ingredient in desserts and sweets, such as cookies.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] They may also be used as a garnish on dishes.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Apple chips are mass-produced by some food manufacturers.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Companies that produce them include Seneca Foods, Bare Fruit, Buddy Fruits and Tyrrell's Bare Fruit and Buddy Fruits apple chips are prepared using only apples as their sole ingredient.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Apple chips can also be made by deep frying a sliced apple in a batter.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Usually, the batter will also be topped with cinnamon before or after the frying process.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] The usual shape of a deep-fried apple chip is a ring.
[src:apple-chip/apple-chip] Fried Apple chips can also be made in a pan.
